The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     CRICKET BRIEFS
                                  
	Shoaib free to appeal  Karachi: Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) chairman Nasim Ashraf has said Shoaib Akhtar is free to appeal against the reduced 18-month ban and the hefty fine imposed on him by the appellate tribunal. Even as Shoaib expressed disappointment at the tribunal rsquo;s verdict, Ashraf said the pacer has the right to go to high court or even the Supreme Court. ldquo;That is his decision. The verdict has nothing to do with the PCB hellip; I can rsquo;t overturn the reduced ban on him. The decision made by justice Aftab Farrukh is final and it can only be challenged in the court, rdquo; Ashraf said. Shoaib, after hearing the decision on Saturday, said he was disappointed, as it was a blow to his career. But he said his lawyer Abid Hasan Minto would go through the judgement before deciding anything.    
	Asif case  Karachi: The attorney general in Dubai took up the Mohammed Asif detention case on Sunday but Pakistan embassy officials do not expect a verdict before another 10 to 12 days. An official in the embassy in Dubai said the attorney general went through the medical reports of Asif and the report of the public prosecutor on the case on Sunday. ldquo;He (the attorney general) will first see the evidence and reports and question the prosecution. After which Asif would be called for questioning as would other defendants, rdquo; the official said.    
	 Lankans move  Colombo: In a bid to promote cricket tourism here, Sri Lankan cricketers Muttiah Muralidharan and Mahela Jayawardene will be in India from Monday to promote next month rsquo;s series against India. Sri Lanka Cricket (SLC) chairman Arjuna Ranatunga will be joined by Aravinda de Silva, Muralidharan, Jayawardene and Kumar Sangakkara to showcase Sri Lanka tourism with the cricket matches as the immediate attraction.     
	 Semis off  Calcutta: Heavy rain and poor ground conditions forced the two CAB league semi-finals to be called off on Sunday. The matches mdash; Kalighat vs ER and BNR vs EB mdash; will now be played from Tuesday while the final will be played on Saturday and Sunday, says A Staff Reporter.    
	 Official launch   Calcutta: The official launch of the ICC Champions Trophy 2008 will take place in Lahore, on Wednesday, says A Staff Reporter as per an ICC release. 
                                                                                                                                                               
